message:
Ohhhh the ironies of the world. I have spent the last year stressing out about internships since a great number of my peers have been getting bomb ass internships across the globe. In the past week I have had four interviews for internship positions and I was actually offered one at a company called 500 startups. 700 people applied, 10 were interviewed, and I was offered the internship at the end of the cycle (omfg). BUT the catch is that it is an internship for the fall and I am going to be attending U of M so I am not able to accept it. 

But for those of you that don't know, I drove down to San Francisco this summer to have a good time and to spend some time with Jared- who I have been dating for about 9ish months (I think it's okay to tag ya in a post now lol). I have only been in SF for ~4 weeks and I have been to 5 or 6 different events/summits/meetups. I will be driving from Cali to Michigan with my brother around August 18th. 

I came to SF not really knowing anyone besides Jared and his roommates, but I somehow got a job on the 5th day I was in the city after some hustling on the good ol' Linkedin and other job sites. Aaaaand it's another one of Kyle's weird jobs. My summer job this year is at a Korean Bibimbop restaurant. Which is essentially a Korean Chipotle. It is located in an international food court in the downtown financial district. Which I was a little bummed about at first- but since it is located where a bunch of fancy business people work AND eat lunch I am able to talk to them when they order food; so I have actually been able to make some valuable contacts with people in the same field I am-- while I am asking them if they would like noodles, rice or lettuce for their bowl of course. 

But I'm excited (and a lil nervous) to see what my future holds in Ann Arbor this coming fall, and to see my Michigan people! 

That's all I got for my Facebook update this time!

message:
Hey o hey people that follow my life on the internet. So I know that I originally said that I was planning on attending Western Washington University this fall. BUT after some thinking and talks with the family, that is not going to happen anymore. I am going to be finishing my Bachelors Degree at the University of Michigan! I am currently enrolled in the school of Art and Design, but I am in the process of being put into the applicant pool for the school of Information, as their curriculum better suits my academic goals. So I may be dual majoring, or getting a single major. I don't really know all of that yet, I just know that Imma be in Ann Arbor this fall.

I am going to miss Seattle's people, the mountains, and the diversity of the city so much. It has been a wild ride and I have met amazing people from all different walks of life. Everyone I have met has an interesting story to share, and I am humbled that so many different people have shared their stories with me. But this is not a goodbye, this is a "see you soon". I don't know what my future holds, but Seattle will always have a special place in my heart, and I defintley can see myself living here at a later stage of my life. 

Living in Seattle has been an amazing experience that I am incredibly grateful for. Seeing LGBTQIA+ people living out and proudly is something that I never saw my entire 18 years of growing up in Rochester Hills. Simply seeing same-sex couples holding hands in a public is empowering and dignifies identities. Because of experiences like these, I have learned first hand how vital representation is for underrepresented communities. The Midwest has never been on the forefront of LGBTQIA+ rights, and I want to bring some of the good ol' west coast gayness back to the mitten. Mindsets can be/need to be changed, and I want the the next generation of queers to see that there are respected gay people out there, and they aren't only in big cities. 

So see you soon Michigan friends and family :)

message:
People ask me all the time why I moved from Michigan to Seattle and I usually never tell them the full truth. 

I moved from Michigan to Seattle because I was so scared of everyone's reactions to me being gay that I literally one night googled "gay friendly cities" and Seattle popped up. There was no other rationale behind it. All I knew about Seattle before I moved here was that it rained and there was coffee. I know that I'm gay all the time and it probably becomes a nuisance, but I still have a very hard time telling people why I moved here.

(I haven't even told my coworker of three months that I'm gay and still pretend that I care about his fantasy football team lol)
Thanks @nintendo

I've been in a Seattle for a year!

And what a year it's been. I started out as a lazy piece of shit, and now I'm just a piece of shit that cooks more. 

Moving out here has honestly been one of the most humiliating experiences, and I am so so grateful for it.

And while I strongly encourage taking a gap year from college I highly recommend getting your math classes out of the way before hand- so you don't test into an algebra one class and beg your professor to let you go into an algebra one/two combo course. 

Making friends is hard. Holy mother of God.

I've had seven jobs in a year lol.

I know how to take a fork out of my car tire. 

I know how to pop a car tire. 

The more you listen the funnier everyone becomes.

I've become much more confident in my beliefs and started developing my own core values and it's nice.

I can't wait to get a degree so I can get a real job and never take out compost ever again.

-until next time 💖

I usually keep my mouth shut on facebook about political jargon but this current issue about the minimum wage is striking me closer to home than Cecil the Lion and other fb trends. 

I am in an interesting position at the moment. I Moved to Seattle last January and the minimum wage was $10ish/hour. The wage raised to $11/hour within two months of me being there and with a proposed raise to $15/hour this coming January. 

I know that I decided fully on my own to move to Seattle and decided to take a different college route than most students.  I went through the process of becoming a resident for a year and then pursuing the four year university path. With that decision comes the bearing of having to support yourself without the help of your parents. 

I started out working 30ish hours a week and having one class at a community college. initially this didn't seem too bad, because I had $3k in the bank that I saved up. I pretty much depleted through money within four months and before ya knew it, it was summer. This was when it hit me that I had to figure some shit out, and I had to fast. I kind of figured it out, and hey I'm still well enough to bitch on fb.

At 30 hours a week I made essentially $1200 a month and had rent at $850. I cannot imagine adding kids and bills into that mix which millions of Americans get landed into. Everyone makes bad choices, mistakes, etc.. (My parents helped me out when I was broke off my ass) That's life, but 

!!!!!
it's not fair that privilege protects some while others get royally shafted. 
!!!!!
